@kamaci, after a look at the Java sources: calling [GZIPInputStream.close()](http://code.metager.de/source/xref/openjdk/jdk8/jdk/src/share/classes/java/util/zip/GZIPInputStream.java#129) calls [InflaterInputStream.close()](http://code.metager.de/source/xref/openjdk/jdk8/jdk/src/share/classes/java/util/zip/InflaterInputStream.java#218) which closes the underlying stream. In ArcRecordReader that's `FSDataInputStream in` which should be kept open until `ArcRecordReader.close()` is called, but not every time `next(...)` is executed (with and without an exception). Only if `ArcRecordReader.close()` is never called the input stream may leak as resource (usually the max. number of open files per process is limited).

GZIPUtils.unzipBestEffort() is different because the underlying ByteArrayInputStream is hold by a local variable.

Given that ArcRecordReader is rarely used (for 1.x it can be used to convert content from ARC files into a Nutch segment, cf. ArcSegmentCreator), I wouldn't personally spent much time for investigation, although I'm curious which opinion is correct. For 2.x we also could consider to remove all ARC related classes.

